135. Dataclasses ⭐
Dataclasses reduce boilerplate code by automatically generating common methods like __init__(), __repr__(), and __eq__() for classes that primarily store data.
A Python dataclass is a regular class enhanced by the @dataclass decorator from the built-in dataclasses module to automatically generate boilerplate "dunder" methods like __init__(), __repr__(), and __eq__()

from dataclasses import dataclass
@dataclass
class Product:
    name: str
    price: float
    quantity: int = 0  # Supports default values
# Instantiation
item = Product(name="Laptop", price=999.99, quantity=2)
# 1. Automatic __repr__ (Easy Debugging)
print(item)  
# Output: Product(name='Laptop', price=999.99, quantity=2)
# 2. Automatic __eq__ (Structural Comparison)
same_item = Product("Laptop", 999.99, 2)
print(item == same_item)  
# Output: True

136. Frozen Dataclasses
Frozen dataclasses create immutable objects.
To make a dataclass frozen, pass frozen=True to the decorator

from dataclasses import dataclass
@dataclass(frozen=True)
class Point:
    x: int
    y: int

p = Point(1, 2)
# p.x = 5  <-- This will raise dataclasses.FrozenInstanceError

137. Walrus Operator (:=)
The walrus operator assigns and returns a value in a single expression.
Example
if (n := len("Python")) > 5:
    print(n)  #6

138. Pattern Matching (Python 3.10+)
Pattern matching is the alternative to multiple if-elif statements.
Pattern matching uses match-case statements to compare values against patterns and execute corresponding code blocks.

value = 2
match value:
    case 1:
        print("One")
    case 2:
        print("Two")

139. f-Strings
f-strings are a python feature that allows you to embedd(Join) both the expressions and variables directly into the strings 

name = "Alice"
age = 28
print(f"My name is {name} and I am {age} years old.")

140. slots ⭐

class Player:
    # Explicitly declare allowed attributes
    __slots__ = ('name', 'level', 'score')
    
    def __init__(self, name, level, score):
        self.name = name
        self.level = level
        self.score = score

# Usage
p = Player("Alice", 10, 500)
print(p.name)  # Works normally

# This will raise an AttributeError because 'inventory' is not in __slots__
p.inventory = ["sword", "shield"] 



























































